At Rose City Smoke Shop, bags of Cascade Roll roll-your-own tobacco from Cascade Leaf Co. were displayed without any health warning, and the manufacturer’s website only shows decorative images with no warning text.

Dorchester Corner Store sold Harbor Lights menthol cigarettes where the pack warning was partially covered by a price sticker, and Harbor Lights Manufacturing promotes discount cartons online without showing required warnings.
At Maple Street Market, Lakeshore Honey cigars from Lakeshore Tobacco Co. were displayed with no visible warning label, and the manufacturer’s promotional flyers promised extra sticks in each bundle.

Gulf Breeze Labs manufactured tropical disposable vapes without proper warnings, and Crescent City Distribution moved the same products into corner stores around New Orleans without checking authorization.
Midwest Leaf Co. produced honey cigars without a full warning, and SouthSide Tobacco Distribution promoted bulk shipments of the same cigars to small stores without any reference to authorization.
Mountain Ridge Tobacco manufactured roll-your-own tobacco bags missing warning panels and partnered with Wasatch Distribution to deliver them to retailers without verifying authorization.

LakeEffect Labs produced nicotine pouches advertised as herbal, and Empire State Distribution moved them into stores in Buffalo even though packaging and online ads do not show the required nicotine warning.
Pacific Ember Co. manufactured cinnamon cigars without full warnings and partnered with Cascade Valley Distribution to move multi-pack bundles into small grocery stores with free-sample signage.
